  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Establish global standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. Regulatory Frameworks\n- Countries adopt similar legal approaches\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International cooperation in investigations\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Extradition agreements\n- Asset seizure and recovery processes\n- Coordinated international law enforcement efforts\n\n5. Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- National agencies that collect and analyze financial data\n- Share intelligence across jurisdictions\n- Coordinate investigations\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- International economic sanctions\n- Targeted financial restrictions\n- Prosecution of transnational financial crimes\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
